WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:07.180
MALE SPEAKER: Good afternoon,
everyone.

00:00:07.180 --> 00:00:10.040
We are extremely thrilled today
to host the Alexander

00:00:10.040 --> 00:00:11.160
String Quartet.

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:14.250
Formed just over 30 years ago,
they're one of the premier

00:00:14.250 --> 00:00:15.840
quartets worldwide.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:20.420
Members Zak Grafilo, Frederick
Lifsitz, Paul Yarbrough, and

00:00:20.420 --> 00:00:23.700
Sandy Wilson are based in San
Francisco, where they serve as

00:00:23.700 --> 00:00:26.660
the ensemble in residence for
San Francisco performances.

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:29.980
You can find more about their
ongoing tours and their

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:35.030
discography at ASQ4.com, while
San Francisco performances is,

00:00:35.030 --> 00:00:37.870
of course, at performances.org.

00:00:37.870 --> 00:00:40.920
The ASQ has completed a series
of string quartet cycles,

00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:43.220
including the complete Beethoven
and the complete

00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:45.790
Shostakovich, both
very well done.

00:00:45.790 --> 00:00:48.880
Their latest works on the
Allegro Media Group include

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:50.990
pieces by Gershwin and Kern.

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:53.730
Today's program will be
announced from the stage, but

00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:56.440
as always, we'll have time
for some Q&amp;A at the end.

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:59.460
After all, what is the string
quartet but the most elevated

00:00:59.460 --> 00:01:02.340
musical conversation
in live music?

00:01:02.340 --> 00:01:04.810
So without further ado, please
join me in welcoming the

00:01:04.810 --> 00:01:06.310
Alexander String Quartet
to Google.

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:07.560
Thanks a lot.

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:11.770
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: It's
an incredible

00:01:11.770 --> 00:01:12.910
pleasure to be here.

00:01:12.910 --> 00:01:15.350
This setting-- this very
setting, with people gathered

00:01:15.350 --> 00:01:19.160
around comfortably, television
cameras, was exactly what

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:22.330
Mozart and Haydn had in mind
when they were composing their

00:01:22.330 --> 00:01:26.240
greatest quartets in the
1780s, and in Haydn

00:01:26.240 --> 00:01:28.130
case, into the 1790s.

00:01:28.130 --> 00:01:32.350
The genre really started in the
1750s. '50s A young Haydn

00:01:32.350 --> 00:01:33.820
started writing some
string quartets.

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:36.730
A great many composers in
southern Germany and northern

00:01:36.730 --> 00:01:39.400
Italy wrote quartets, although
the instruments had been

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:41.640
around for some time
before that.

00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:44.200
But this idea of the
conversation in the music was

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:46.510
really paramount to the
string quartet.

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:50.190
And as I said, Haydn and his
younger counterpart Mozart did

00:01:50.190 --> 00:01:53.800
everything they could to bring
the quartet to the point when

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:57.470
Mozart died in 1791, the quartet
was just a vehicle

00:01:57.470 --> 00:02:01.170
that was going to last,
and it did last.

00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:03.480
Almost every great composer
to this very day has

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:05.200
written at least one.

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:08.430
We used to have garages full
of scores sent to us from

00:02:08.430 --> 00:02:09.479
composers around the world.

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:14.210
Now we have mailboxes full of
them in electronic format.

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:16.220
It hasn't stopped.

00:02:16.220 --> 00:02:19.330
This first work we're going to
play for you is one of the

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:21.340
last quartets that
Mozart wrote.

00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:24.610
In fact, I think this is the
last quartet that he wrote.

00:02:24.610 --> 00:02:26.410
Not the last work.

00:02:26.410 --> 00:02:31.180
This dates June of 1790, and
he and Haydn had written

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:33.910
quartets back and forth for each
other, and they actually

00:02:33.910 --> 00:02:37.020
played in a quartet together
with two other composers.

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:40.630
It would've been wonderful to
eavesdrop on those evenings.

00:02:40.630 --> 00:02:44.330
But this quartet was written
as a set of three--

00:02:44.330 --> 00:02:46.840
one of a set of three that was
dedicated to the King of

00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:49.320
Prussia, who was an
amateur cellist.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:51.840
He was either a really great
cellist, or Mozart really

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:54.780
wanted to impress him, because
the cello writing is extremely

00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:56.620
difficult in this work.

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:58.380
No pressure, Sandy.

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:00.900
And we're going to share
with you the first

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:02.530
movement of this quartet.

00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:06.090
It starts off using the forces
in absolute unison, and

00:03:06.090 --> 00:03:07.340
branches out from there.

00:03:14.250 --> 00:12:01.740
[MUSIC - MOZART]

00:12:01.740 --> 00:12:03.950
PAUL YARBROUGH: For our next
selection, we've chosen to

00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:09.080
play two movements from a
quartet by Franz Schubert.

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:13.250
Schubert was born just a few
years after Mozart's death.

00:12:13.250 --> 00:12:20.490
He was born in the same city,
Vienna, in 1797, and lived

00:12:20.490 --> 00:12:23.310
only until 1828.

00:12:23.310 --> 00:12:28.240
He died at the age of
31, having written

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:29.900
more than 1,000 works.

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:33.460
He was an incredibly prolific
composer for

00:12:33.460 --> 00:12:35.160
such a short lifespan.

00:12:35.160 --> 00:12:37.810
I think he did nothing but
write music pretty

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:39.060
much all day long.

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:45.570
The two movements that we'd like
to play from a quartet

00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:49.060
that has a nickname, Death
and the Maiden.

00:12:49.060 --> 00:12:54.800
This quartet was written
after a poem by a man

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:56.460
named Matthias Claudius.

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:58.900
And the poem is very short.

00:12:58.900 --> 00:13:02.780
And first, Schubert wrote a
song on the poem, and the

00:13:02.780 --> 00:13:08.880
story is, death has come to take
away this young girl, and

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:11.122
he's very seductive.

00:13:11.122 --> 00:13:15.310
And he says, come with me.

00:13:15.310 --> 00:13:16.410
You're going to love it.

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:17.880
It's great.

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:19.400
She says, no, no, no.

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:20.220
I'm too young.

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:21.200
I can't go yet.

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:24.380
And he says, no,
you're coming.

00:13:24.380 --> 00:13:26.610
So basically, that's the poem.

00:13:26.610 --> 00:13:29.550
And the singer who sings
it has to kind

00:13:29.550 --> 00:13:31.260
of do both the voices--

00:13:31.260 --> 00:13:35.510
the voice of the maiden and
the voice of death.

00:13:35.510 --> 00:13:39.750
Anyway, later on, after having
written the song, Schubert

00:13:39.750 --> 00:13:44.280
wrote a variations movement on
the theme from the song, and

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:47.000
that's the movement that we're
going to play from the string

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.880
quartet, which then took the
title of the poem as its

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:54.110
nickname for the
entire quartet.

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:59.000
The quartet, which is four
movements, is very much in the

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:03.540
same vein as the poem, and
there's an amazing thing that

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:05.410
Schubert does, which
is going between

00:14:05.410 --> 00:14:09.450
a dark minor tonality--

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:11.090
very ominous--

00:14:11.090 --> 00:14:14.150
to something that's brighter,
more optimistic.

00:14:14.150 --> 00:14:18.120
Not necessarily happy,
but kind of serene.

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:21.380
And it's such a beautiful
juxtaposition between these

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:24.920
two poles of expression.

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:27.460
The first movement that we'll
play is actually the second

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:32.460
movement from the quartet, and
it's titled Andante Con Moto.

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:35.720
And this is the theme and
variation of movement.

00:14:35.720 --> 00:14:40.130
And then we'll also play the
following movements, Scherzo

00:14:40.130 --> 00:14:43.710
and Trio, and in that movement,
you'll hear the

00:14:43.710 --> 00:14:47.050
contrast between the minor
and the major and the

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:48.300
darkness and the light.

00:15:03.589 --> 00:15:04.839
[MUSIC - FRANZ SCHUBERT,
"DEATH AND THE MAIDEN"]

00:28:58.789 --> 00:29:01.150
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: It's
interesting that Schubert and

00:29:01.150 --> 00:29:04.890
Beethoven were alive, working
quite hard at the same time,

00:29:04.890 --> 00:29:06.960
at the end of both
of their lives.

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:09.950
And Schubert and Beethoven, as
far as we know, never met.

00:29:09.950 --> 00:29:12.050
They lived within blocks
of one another.

00:29:12.050 --> 00:29:15.020
And despite this impression of
Beethoven being this very

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:17.810
tall, imposing figure that you
see in statues, especially in

00:29:17.810 --> 00:29:20.200
Vienna, he apparently
was quite short.

00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:22.390
And Schubert was even shorter.

00:29:22.390 --> 00:29:25.980
And Schubert was very shy, and
he just apparently could never

00:29:25.980 --> 00:29:29.400
get up the nerve to go and speak
to Beethoven, of course,

00:29:29.400 --> 00:29:31.600
which was difficult also toward
the end of Beethoven's

00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:33.740
life with hearing issues.

00:29:33.740 --> 00:29:36.560
But Beethoven, at the end
of his life, did ask his

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:40.230
assistant to bring in some of
the scores of this young

00:29:40.230 --> 00:29:42.410
gentleman's music, and
was really, really

00:29:42.410 --> 00:29:43.260
blown away by it.

00:29:43.260 --> 00:29:45.380
He could read it like a book.

00:29:45.380 --> 00:29:51.300
The other kind of ultimate spam
box was the coat room in

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:52.480
the home of [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:52.480 --> 00:29:55.410
the great poet, playwright,
and philosopher.

00:29:55.410 --> 00:29:58.230
He had an assistant that sort
of screened his mail.

00:29:58.230 --> 00:30:01.590
And Schubert had a handful
of songs--

00:30:01.590 --> 00:30:04.850
of poems of [INAUDIBLE]
he had put to music.

00:30:04.850 --> 00:30:08.865
Those poems, those songs, the
lieder that he wrote, have

00:30:08.865 --> 00:30:12.480
been what has made a lot of
[INAUDIBLE] poetry famous in

00:30:12.480 --> 00:30:14.640
every region of the world, where
it probably wouldn't

00:30:14.640 --> 00:30:15.970
have been read otherwise.

00:30:15.970 --> 00:30:17.480
But at the time, [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:17.480 --> 00:30:19.700
didn't really know who this guy
was, and never opened it

00:30:19.700 --> 00:30:24.440
to see the manuscript of these
songs that had been written

00:30:24.440 --> 00:30:27.020
based on his poetry.

00:30:27.020 --> 00:30:30.600
These composers, looking back,
with hindsight, you can always

00:30:30.600 --> 00:30:31.670
tell a good one.

00:30:31.670 --> 00:30:36.020
But at the time, it's really
hard to see what a winner is.

00:30:36.020 --> 00:30:40.280
But somehow, time seems to have
been very kind to these

00:30:40.280 --> 00:30:43.080
handful of composers, and you'd
think that the string

00:30:43.080 --> 00:30:45.790
quartet was only written and
played in Vienna, if you heard

00:30:45.790 --> 00:30:47.420
the first part of
this program.

00:30:47.420 --> 00:30:50.240
But we're going to move to the
20th century, and to England.

00:30:50.240 --> 00:30:54.270
Not necessarily to London, but
to England, and the composer

00:30:54.270 --> 00:30:55.990
Benjamin Britten.

00:30:55.990 --> 00:31:00.700
Britten wrote three beautiful
string quartets, and he wrote

00:31:00.700 --> 00:31:02.310
earlier than he wrote
the string quartets.

00:31:02.310 --> 00:31:05.670
In 1933, when he was
20 years old--

00:31:05.670 --> 00:31:08.180
19, I guess, officially when
he wrote these works.

00:31:08.180 --> 00:31:13.320
He was born, as I said in
1913, and died in 1976.

00:31:13.320 --> 00:31:16.470
He wrote three divertimenti.

00:31:16.470 --> 00:31:19.140
Three sort of fun pieces,
although I wouldn't

00:31:19.140 --> 00:31:21.490
necessarily call these
necessarily fun pieces.

00:31:21.490 --> 00:31:24.835
But they are fun to play, and
they're fun to listen to.

00:31:24.835 --> 00:31:27.320
But as was anything with
Benjamin Britten's music,

00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:29.550
there's a note of seriousness.

00:31:29.550 --> 00:31:31.130
He was a lifelong pacifist.

00:31:31.130 --> 00:31:34.430
As a boy in boarding school,
he witnessed beatings that

00:31:34.430 --> 00:31:37.750
were condoned, and perhaps that
was that type of thing

00:31:37.750 --> 00:31:40.610
that led him to become a
conscientious objector during

00:31:40.610 --> 00:31:41.430
World War II.

00:31:41.430 --> 00:31:42.770
He was in this country.

00:31:42.770 --> 00:31:45.530
He wrote the famous War Requiem,
which is a real

00:31:45.530 --> 00:31:48.160
statement against man's
inhumanity to man.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:51.280
And he took his own art--
used his own art

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:52.940
to express his feelings.

00:31:52.940 --> 00:31:56.460
His innermost feelings about the
way he viewed the world.

00:31:56.460 --> 00:31:59.580
Composers have often used the
string quartet, because it's

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:03.700
this incredibly transparent,
intimate art form, to express

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:05.680
some of these feelings that
they perhaps otherwise

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:09.240
wouldn't express in an opera or
in a symphony, or in some

00:32:09.240 --> 00:32:10.560
larger scale work.

00:32:10.560 --> 00:32:13.370
Shostakovich did that and
in the Soviet Union.

00:32:13.370 --> 00:32:16.360
When he had something to say
that he didn't want to be too

00:32:16.360 --> 00:32:21.060
scrutinized by the upper echelon
of the government, so

00:32:21.060 --> 00:32:22.960
he put it in a string quartet--
sort of worked it

00:32:22.960 --> 00:32:24.870
into his music.

00:32:24.870 --> 00:32:27.490
And the string quartet
typically has a small

00:32:27.490 --> 00:32:31.450
audience, so it didn't get the
kind of feature that his

00:32:31.450 --> 00:32:34.390
operas, which often got
him into trouble, did.

00:32:34.390 --> 00:32:37.290
But this work by Britten is
just a charming work.

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:41.295
Britten, a lot like Schubert, a
lot like Mozart, was writing

00:32:41.295 --> 00:32:43.330
music from a very,
very young age.

00:32:43.330 --> 00:32:45.030
Felix Mendelssohn
was another one.

00:32:45.030 --> 00:32:47.640
Music just seemed to come
out of their pores.

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:50.840
And his mother, Benjamin
Britten's mother, fully

00:32:50.840 --> 00:32:55.220
anticipated that her son would
become the fourth B--

00:32:55.220 --> 00:32:58.700
after Bach, Beethoven,
and Brahms.

00:32:58.700 --> 00:33:01.310
Brahms lived in great fear that
Bruckner would become the

00:33:01.310 --> 00:33:04.525
fourth B. But Britten--

00:33:04.525 --> 00:33:06.660
I don't know if he's considered
the fourth B, but

00:33:06.660 --> 00:33:08.000
we love his music.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:09.530
This is three movements.

00:33:09.530 --> 00:33:13.030
The first is a march, and the
second movement is a beautiful

00:33:13.030 --> 00:33:16.030
waltz, and the third movement is
a very almost rambunctious

00:33:16.030 --> 00:33:16.960
country dance.

00:33:16.960 --> 00:33:19.690
He wrote this pieces, I believe,
as descriptions of

00:33:19.690 --> 00:33:23.210
three of his good friends
from his youth.

00:33:23.210 --> 00:33:26.430
And I don't know much more
about them, but you can

00:33:26.430 --> 00:33:29.035
extrapolate what you can from
hearing these three vignettes.

00:33:47.712 --> 00:33:51.780
The repertoire is so fast that
if we spent, as we have, our

00:33:51.780 --> 00:33:53.360
entire adult lives--

00:33:53.360 --> 00:33:55.720
supposedly we are adults--

00:33:55.720 --> 00:33:57.420
playing this music, we'll never
get through it all.

00:33:57.420 --> 00:33:59.480
Not on the level that
we want to play it.

00:33:59.480 --> 00:34:01.460
So we're very fortunate
in terms of that.

00:34:01.460 --> 00:34:04.780
And the vehicle, the string
quartet as an art form, and as

00:34:04.780 --> 00:34:10.969
a vehicle for music, and to go
places as an ensemble is

00:34:10.969 --> 00:34:11.274
remarkable.

00:34:11.274 --> 00:34:14.260
The four of us, all we really
need are four chairs, although

00:34:14.260 --> 00:34:15.810
we could play three
of us standing up.

00:34:15.810 --> 00:34:17.699
And Sandy actually doesn't sound
too bad when he stands

00:34:17.699 --> 00:34:20.210
up with the cello.

00:34:20.210 --> 00:34:22.679
I think he and Yo Yo Ma have
the record on that.

00:34:22.679 --> 00:34:24.190
But four chairs.

00:34:24.190 --> 00:34:27.060
We bring our own stands with us,
we buy a seat for Sandy's

00:34:27.060 --> 00:34:28.510
cello wherever we
go in the world.

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:31.290
It often flies first
or business class.

00:34:31.290 --> 00:34:32.780
It doesn't play word
or anything.

00:34:32.780 --> 00:34:33.420
SANDY WILSON: [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:33.420 --> 00:34:35.489
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: Sometimes he
does, sometimes he doesn't.

00:34:35.489 --> 00:34:38.170
But if you see four people with
instruments sitting in

00:34:38.170 --> 00:34:41.260
four separate sections
of the plane, it's

00:34:41.260 --> 00:34:42.830
probably a string quartet.

00:34:42.830 --> 00:34:44.860
And not speaking
to each other.

00:34:44.860 --> 00:34:46.560
But we do spend a lot
of time together.

00:34:46.560 --> 00:34:50.030
And the four of us can go into
a wonderful setting like this

00:34:50.030 --> 00:34:50.790
here at Google.

00:34:50.790 --> 00:34:53.050
We can go in, as we do,
through San Francisco

00:34:53.050 --> 00:34:56.760
Performances, through
so many other means.

00:34:56.760 --> 00:35:00.130
Into classrooms, into inner
city schools to play in an

00:35:00.130 --> 00:35:03.950
even closer setting than this--
children, high school

00:35:03.950 --> 00:35:06.870
students, who perhaps never had
the opportunity to hear

00:35:06.870 --> 00:35:10.010
something like this in their
lives, and they stand or sit

00:35:10.010 --> 00:35:12.840
three feet away from Sandy's
cello or something.

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:16.030
They can feel the vibrations in
a way that their electronic

00:35:16.030 --> 00:35:19.400
reproductions just don't give
when they listen to music, and

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:21.560
it becomes an extraordinary
visceral experience.

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:24.870
So the quartet as an art form is
a lot easier to get around

00:35:24.870 --> 00:35:26.210
than a symphony.

00:35:26.210 --> 00:35:28.670
The repertoire is vast.

00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:31.050
Not to be mistaken that I
don't value symphonic

00:35:31.050 --> 00:35:32.160
repertoire, or other things.

00:35:32.160 --> 00:35:35.700
You don't have to tune it like
a piano-- you just tune 16

00:35:35.700 --> 00:35:38.850
strings instead of 600.

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:41.170
But now it's your turn.

00:35:41.170 --> 00:35:43.950
If you have any questions at
all, anything you've been

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:45.640
dying to know, anything
you'd like to--

00:35:45.640 --> 00:35:46.150
please.

00:35:46.150 --> 00:35:47.270
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:35:47.270 --> 00:35:49.070
Can you tell us a bit more about
the circumstances under

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:52.480
which some of the early quartets
of Mozart, Haydn,

00:35:52.480 --> 00:35:53.540
Beethoven, were performed?

00:35:53.540 --> 00:35:55.960
Were they done for members of
the public, or for friends?

00:35:55.960 --> 00:35:58.480
Did they do an entire couple of
quartets in an evening, or

00:35:58.480 --> 00:36:00.000
did they just play in
[INAUDIBLE] movements?

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:01.410
Things like that.

00:36:01.410 --> 00:36:04.330
PAUL YARBROUGH: Well,
great question.

00:36:04.330 --> 00:36:07.720
Something we have to bear in
mind when we play this music,

00:36:07.720 --> 00:36:11.440
that it was almost entirely
inaccessible to the general

00:36:11.440 --> 00:36:13.070
public, really.

00:36:13.070 --> 00:36:15.660
It was the domain of
the aristocracy.

00:36:15.660 --> 00:36:20.940
These were people who lived in
palaces, and had the funds to

00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:25.630
have a retinue of musicians,
perhaps in their employ.

00:36:25.630 --> 00:36:31.480
Or they were just from finer
families in Vienna who would

00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:34.940
have musicales and would
invite the interesting

00:36:34.940 --> 00:36:37.910
musicians of the day to come
and perform in their home.

00:36:37.910 --> 00:36:41.390
And if you were fortunate enough
to have an invitation,

00:36:41.390 --> 00:36:42.700
you could hear the music.

00:36:42.700 --> 00:36:46.430
Or if you were among the very
few people, but a growing

00:36:46.430 --> 00:36:51.770
class of people, who actually
were beginning to rise up into

00:36:51.770 --> 00:36:56.400
a sort of a beginning middle
class, and those people could

00:36:56.400 --> 00:36:59.890
actually afford to learn to play
instruments and enjoy the

00:36:59.890 --> 00:37:02.820
music in their own--

00:37:02.820 --> 00:37:04.650
this music has two purposes.

00:37:04.650 --> 00:37:07.270
One is a performance aspect,
and the other is a

00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:08.760
participation aspect.

00:37:08.760 --> 00:37:14.700
And so during the early years,
it was considered a mark of

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:18.870
very good training and breeding
that you could take a

00:37:18.870 --> 00:37:22.260
hand and play a part in the
string quartet with other

00:37:22.260 --> 00:37:27.260
people who are like minded, and
that was a sort of, you

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:32.370
might say, kind of an
enlightenment idea, that

00:37:32.370 --> 00:37:34.860
everyone could play and
participate in this music,

00:37:34.860 --> 00:37:37.160
which is such a rarefied
thing.

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:40.390
And those people, when they came
to hear a concert or a

00:37:40.390 --> 00:37:44.730
performance of some kind,
had high expectations.

00:37:44.730 --> 00:37:48.820
They knew the music, how it
would be structured, what was

00:37:48.820 --> 00:37:51.110
likely to be the formal
structure of each of the

00:37:51.110 --> 00:37:53.120
movements in the quartet.

00:37:53.120 --> 00:37:58.640
And there wasn't the same
prohibition against clapping

00:37:58.640 --> 00:38:02.230
between movements, or even, at
that point, during movements.

00:38:02.230 --> 00:38:06.220
If you were turned on by
something that was done in the

00:38:06.220 --> 00:38:10.540
moment, just like you would in
a jazz performance, somebody

00:38:10.540 --> 00:38:14.850
takes a solo and everybody
claps, and then it moves on.

00:38:14.850 --> 00:38:19.420
But that was not so unusual
in those times.

00:38:19.420 --> 00:38:25.190
Now it's become very stiff,
which we try, to some extent,

00:38:25.190 --> 00:38:31.040
to counteract the stuffiness
or formality of classical

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:31.920
music concerts.

00:38:31.920 --> 00:38:34.760
On the other hand, we
appreciate, too, when people

00:38:34.760 --> 00:38:37.920
are really attentive and silent,
and not clinking

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:40.980
glasses and talking loudly
and so forth.

00:38:40.980 --> 00:38:44.810
So I know some of the jazz
musicians, we say, [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:44.810 --> 00:38:46.700
club environment is so cool.

00:38:46.700 --> 00:38:49.720
It seems so personal
and so unstuffy.

00:38:49.720 --> 00:38:52.310
And they say, yeah, but people
are drinking and talking while

00:38:52.310 --> 00:38:53.730
you're playing.

00:38:53.730 --> 00:38:55.560
They kind of crave
what we have--

00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:57.960
the silent audience
in a concert hall.

00:38:57.960 --> 00:39:00.910
I hope I answered your
question adequately.

00:39:00.910 --> 00:39:03.100
ZAKARIAS GRAFILO: There's also
some wonderful stories of the

00:39:03.100 --> 00:39:05.170
composers themselves
playing together--

00:39:05.170 --> 00:39:09.200
Mozart and Haydn getting
together, reading through

00:39:09.200 --> 00:39:11.910
their latest string quartets,
and that's kind of how they

00:39:11.910 --> 00:39:12.270
communicated.

00:39:12.270 --> 00:39:15.800
It was like, I can do that
better than you kind of thing.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:19.330
But, I mean, for us, musicians,
thinking about

00:39:19.330 --> 00:39:21.490
being a fly on the wall,
watching some of these reading

00:39:21.490 --> 00:39:23.070
sessions, is just amazing.

00:39:23.070 --> 00:39:25.870
I wish I could go back and see
what that must have been like

00:39:25.870 --> 00:39:28.340
during first performances
of those works.

00:39:28.340 --> 00:39:32.000
AUDIENCE: So I'm curious if
you could comment on--

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.040
there's a lot of discussion
about the impact of technology

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:38.150
on the music industry lately,
and the transition to digital.

00:39:38.150 --> 00:39:40.505
And a lot of that is more about
popular music, and I

00:39:40.505 --> 00:39:42.760
know classical is sort of a much
smaller niche in terms of

00:39:42.760 --> 00:39:43.560
the recording industry.

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:46.560
But if you could comment on what
impact that's had on your

00:39:46.560 --> 00:39:49.650
career, which has obviously
spanned that transition, and

00:39:49.650 --> 00:39:50.910
also how you feel like
it's impacted

00:39:50.910 --> 00:39:53.110
classical music overall.

00:39:53.110 --> 00:39:55.340
SANDY WILSON: I think
very well.

00:39:55.340 --> 00:39:57.870
I think we're still here,
we're thriving.

00:39:57.870 --> 00:39:59.250
We actually--

00:39:59.250 --> 00:40:01.450
over 30 years, we've certainly
seen a lot of changes.

00:40:01.450 --> 00:40:05.050
It's a hell of a lot less
expensive to record now, and

00:40:05.050 --> 00:40:08.640
the ability to record really
well, and to control the

00:40:08.640 --> 00:40:17.290
circumstances under which your
work is encoded for posterity.

00:40:17.290 --> 00:40:20.550
We have a lot more influence
over that.

00:40:20.550 --> 00:40:22.140
Of course, it's prolific.

00:40:22.140 --> 00:40:26.460
And the ability to saturate the
market with substandard

00:40:26.460 --> 00:40:29.600
work is unfortunate.

00:40:29.600 --> 00:40:33.890
PAUL YARBROUGH: Along those
lines, we actually, after many

00:40:33.890 --> 00:40:38.100
unfortunate experiences of
recording and trying to have

00:40:38.100 --> 00:40:45.210
our work distributed well, and
nurtured, if you will, after

00:40:45.210 --> 00:40:49.320
the fact of our making
recordings, we decided the

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:52.810
only alternative was to
make our own company.

00:40:52.810 --> 00:40:58.470
So we started our own record
label about 20 years ago.

00:40:58.470 --> 00:41:02.990
We have done work for other
labels, but we pride ourselves

00:41:02.990 --> 00:41:11.230
in this set of recordings that
we've made, and the amount of

00:41:11.230 --> 00:41:15.420
time and love we lavish
on these projects--

00:41:15.420 --> 00:41:20.280
not only the musical side of it,
but also the information

00:41:20.280 --> 00:41:23.790
inside the booklets, and the
photography, and the graphic

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:25.040
design, and everything.

00:41:27.420 --> 00:41:32.090
We read now that most people
under a certain age have never

00:41:32.090 --> 00:41:34.580
even bought a CD.

00:41:34.580 --> 00:41:38.040
They get everything
electronically, and probably

00:41:38.040 --> 00:41:40.110
without paying for it.

00:41:40.110 --> 00:41:43.450
So that's a matter
of some concern.

00:41:43.450 --> 00:41:47.730
But I still think there are a
lot of people who like the

00:41:47.730 --> 00:41:52.350
physical, the tangible product,
and don't mind buying

00:41:52.350 --> 00:41:54.520
it and keeping it.

00:41:54.520 --> 00:42:00.490
Maybe then they put it on their
different devices and

00:42:00.490 --> 00:42:05.260
use it in different ways, but I,
for one, still like to sit

00:42:05.260 --> 00:42:08.270
down and look at liner notes
while I listen to a piece of

00:42:08.270 --> 00:42:13.370
music, and enjoy whatever
commentary the artists

00:42:13.370 --> 00:42:16.750
themselves might have included
in the booklet.

00:42:16.750 --> 00:42:19.900
So hopefully there's still going
to be a market for just

00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:22.630
hard products of recordings.

00:42:22.630 --> 00:42:28.260
But the other thing is, we do
have to be a little bit

00:42:28.260 --> 00:42:31.250
involved in this change, in the

00:42:31.250 --> 00:42:32.510
revolution that's involved.

00:42:35.580 --> 00:42:42.430
We play 250-year-old
instruments, and 200 and

00:42:42.430 --> 00:42:45.730
something year old music a
lot of the time, and all.

00:42:45.730 --> 00:42:50.410
But we're still 21st century
artists, and we need to be up

00:42:50.410 --> 00:42:52.930
to date, at least somewhat.

00:42:52.930 --> 00:42:55.290
Anyway, I don't know
if that's a good--

00:42:55.290 --> 00:42:56.980
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: I want to
add that my friends who've

00:42:56.980 --> 00:43:01.710
done very well, often in
[INAUDIBLE], have all been

00:43:01.710 --> 00:43:05.380
buying vinyl, and paying a lot
of money, in some cases, for

00:43:05.380 --> 00:43:07.600
record covers that have smudges
on them and other

00:43:07.600 --> 00:43:09.580
things, sometimes with great
history-- which you can't do

00:43:09.580 --> 00:43:11.150
with certain other things.

00:43:11.150 --> 00:43:12.060
So it's kind of--

00:43:12.060 --> 00:43:15.020
I know it's a small niche, but
it's an interesting thing.

00:43:15.020 --> 00:43:17.940
And a lot of the great recording
engineers we work

00:43:17.940 --> 00:43:23.100
say that the analog still is
their preferred mode of

00:43:23.100 --> 00:43:24.580
listening to things.

00:43:24.580 --> 00:43:28.300
And so it depends on
who you talk to.

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:31.320
But the control issue that
Sandy [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:31.320 --> 00:43:35.130
I mean, we did a Beethoven cycle
for BMG years ago, and I

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:37.350
think at a certain point,
it just got buried.

00:43:37.350 --> 00:43:42.150
And they owned it anywhere in
the universe, in any format.

00:43:42.150 --> 00:43:45.820
And then when we did our own,
they rereleased our old one to

00:43:45.820 --> 00:43:47.230
try to compete with it.

00:43:47.230 --> 00:43:49.340
And that's just the way
the world works.

00:43:49.340 --> 00:43:50.920
But we had the choice
to do our own.

00:43:50.920 --> 00:43:54.140
And as Paul also mentioned,
old music.

00:43:54.140 --> 00:43:56.720
But we do a lot of new music,
too, and are able to

00:43:56.720 --> 00:43:59.030
commission works through
friends, and

00:43:59.030 --> 00:44:00.830
through other means--

00:44:00.830 --> 00:44:01.490
foundations.

00:44:01.490 --> 00:44:04.460
And that's a very vital thing--
part of what we feel

00:44:04.460 --> 00:44:08.170
is that the quartet shouldn't
be a museum piece.

00:44:08.170 --> 00:44:11.340
It really should be living
today as well.

00:44:11.340 --> 00:44:13.850
ZAKARIAS GRAFILO: I want to say
also, of course, wonderful

00:44:13.850 --> 00:44:20.350
technologies that are costly,
and therefore, I think they

00:44:20.350 --> 00:44:25.010
still remain in the domain
of the major mega labels.

00:44:25.010 --> 00:44:28.520
But we have had a chance to do
some surround sound recordings

00:44:28.520 --> 00:44:34.240
recently, 24-bit, the extra
dimensions, and we actually

00:44:34.240 --> 00:44:35.750
haven't heard the results
of that yet.

00:44:35.750 --> 00:44:39.210
So the vote's still out on
whether it's something we

00:44:39.210 --> 00:44:40.060
should aspire to.

00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:42.930
But I know that there are
wonderful technologies.

00:44:42.930 --> 00:44:45.600
One thing that we would love to
try to figure out how to do

00:44:45.600 --> 00:44:50.800
is to manage to record in an
acoustical setting in a way

00:44:50.800 --> 00:44:52.650
that we could isolate
our voices.

00:44:55.510 --> 00:44:59.030
Sort of in a pie
sort of sense.

00:44:59.030 --> 00:45:03.330
So you can do music minus
one, or two, or three.

00:45:03.330 --> 00:45:08.170
And I know an awful lot of
very accomplished amateur

00:45:08.170 --> 00:45:12.240
musicians would love
to sit in.

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:14.790
So we've yet to figure out
how to manage that.

00:45:14.790 --> 00:45:15.510
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: Or
if he just got tired

00:45:15.510 --> 00:45:16.070
of hearing me play.

00:45:16.070 --> 00:45:16.220
SANDY WILSON: Quadrophonic.

00:45:16.220 --> 00:45:17.640
Yeah.

00:45:17.640 --> 00:45:22.690
But the act of actually doing it
is still a challenge, with

00:45:22.690 --> 00:45:24.950
accomplishing that isolation
and still keeping the

00:45:24.950 --> 00:45:27.170
sightlines and--

00:45:27.170 --> 00:45:30.210
anyway, that's just things
to play around with.

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:31.520
AUDIENCE: I have
two questions.

00:45:31.520 --> 00:45:34.730
One is that I'm very curious
about your individual

00:45:34.730 --> 00:45:35.680
instruments.

00:45:35.680 --> 00:45:38.680
If you can show us, and then
maybe tell me about those

00:45:38.680 --> 00:45:41.420
things-- like, how many years
old, and how you like it, and

00:45:41.420 --> 00:45:42.350
kind of stuff.

00:45:42.350 --> 00:45:45.560
And the other thing is that I
was sitting over there, and

00:45:45.560 --> 00:45:47.200
there was a speaker there.

00:45:47.200 --> 00:45:51.140
It really magnifies the music in
one way or another, and I'm

00:45:51.140 --> 00:45:55.350
really, really curious to see
without anything at all.

00:45:55.350 --> 00:45:58.850
And then what it used to be,
when they had in a castle, in

00:45:58.850 --> 00:46:00.830
a [? new ?] room, and
listening to.

00:46:00.830 --> 00:46:03.180
So I was wondering if we can get
the opportunity to have to

00:46:03.180 --> 00:46:04.490
have that experience.

00:46:04.490 --> 00:46:05.890
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: I'll give it
a shot, like the emperor's

00:46:05.890 --> 00:46:07.090
new clothes.

00:46:07.090 --> 00:46:08.120
First, about the instruments.

00:46:08.120 --> 00:46:09.080
You want to start?

00:46:09.080 --> 00:46:10.530
Start with the first violin.

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:13.335
ZAKARIAS GRAFILO: This is a
modern fiddle made in 1992, by

00:46:13.335 --> 00:46:15.340
a German maker named
Michael Fisher.

00:46:15.340 --> 00:46:18.880
It's a copy of a [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:20.550
SANDY WILSON: You
played that--

00:46:20.550 --> 00:46:22.360
we actually played
at the Library of

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:24.060
Congress quite recently.

00:46:26.840 --> 00:46:29.700
ZAKARIAS GRAFILO: There's a real
model at the Library of

00:46:29.700 --> 00:46:32.370
Congress that was owned by Fritz
Kreisler that I played

00:46:32.370 --> 00:46:34.920
on a couple years ago, which
is-- when I played on it, I

00:46:34.920 --> 00:46:35.170
was like, wow.

00:46:35.170 --> 00:46:36.440
It's like my old violin.

00:46:36.440 --> 00:46:40.890
So I was quite pleased to
play on that violin.

00:46:40.890 --> 00:46:43.120
SANDY WILSON: The security
folks were kind of--

00:46:43.120 --> 00:46:44.800
ZAKARIAS GRAFILO: They were
