cello at home.

00:47:40.205 --> 00:47:42.873
And if ever you want to buy
a nice 19th century French

00:47:42.873 --> 00:47:45.630
cello, see me afterwards.

00:47:45.630 --> 00:47:50.490
But this was the gold medal
winner in the [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:50.490 --> 00:47:56.520
violin building competition in
that year, and I love it.

00:47:56.520 --> 00:48:00.110
We can tell you a little bit
about why we play modern

00:48:00.110 --> 00:48:02.050
instruments--

00:48:02.050 --> 00:48:02.610
some of us.

00:48:02.610 --> 00:48:04.060
PAUL YARBROUGH: Or
why I don't.

00:48:04.060 --> 00:48:04.960
SANDY WILSON: He can't
afford it.

00:48:04.960 --> 00:48:08.300
He wouldn't have paid them
enough, actually.

00:48:08.300 --> 00:48:12.950
PAUL YARBROUGH: This is the only
instrument in the quartet

00:48:12.950 --> 00:48:15.480
that actually could have
participated in the premier

00:48:15.480 --> 00:48:19.380
performance of any of these
works that we play today,

00:48:19.380 --> 00:48:24.100
because it was made in
1750 in Genoa, Italy.

00:48:24.100 --> 00:48:25.785
The maker's name is Costello.

00:48:30.730 --> 00:48:34.640
I play modern instruments, too,
from time to time, and I

00:48:34.640 --> 00:48:37.580
often love them very much.

00:48:37.580 --> 00:48:42.180
It's sort of a myth
that the only good

00:48:42.180 --> 00:48:44.990
instruments are old ones.

00:48:44.990 --> 00:48:49.260
Instruments do tend to improve
with age, but if they weren't

00:48:49.260 --> 00:48:52.020
really great to start with,
they're not going to become

00:48:52.020 --> 00:48:53.960
great with time.

00:48:53.960 --> 00:48:58.280
So finding an instrument that's
really right for you as

00:48:58.280 --> 00:49:01.270
an individual that you're
able to express

00:49:01.270 --> 00:49:03.720
yourself on is the trick.

00:49:03.720 --> 00:49:10.520
And if you're lucky enough to
be able to find a new one,

00:49:10.520 --> 00:49:13.680
that's nice, because it's
a lot less expensive.

00:49:13.680 --> 00:49:18.790
The old ones are very valuable
for antique and collectible

00:49:18.790 --> 00:49:22.920
reasons, but not necessarily for
the quality of the sound

00:49:22.920 --> 00:49:23.810
that they make.

00:49:23.810 --> 00:49:25.680
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: With the
exception of the really great

00:49:25.680 --> 00:49:29.380
ones, and we're talking about
instruments, in many cases,

00:49:29.380 --> 00:49:31.260
that are Stradivari and
[INAUDIBLE] instruments that

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:34.750
are valued at about $5
millsion, $6 million.

00:49:34.750 --> 00:49:39.530
And none of us want to sell
our children or pets or

00:49:39.530 --> 00:49:40.450
anything to buy them.

00:49:40.450 --> 00:49:41.650
PAUL YARBROUGH: I don't
think my kids would

00:49:41.650 --> 00:49:43.340
bring that much, actually.

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:45.480
But I'd think about it.

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:47.330
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: But
they are magnificent.

00:49:47.330 --> 00:49:50.380
I have to say that when we get
together and play with friends

00:49:50.380 --> 00:49:52.530
who do play on these
instruments, and hear them

00:49:52.530 --> 00:49:55.910
side by side, these
do very well.

00:49:55.910 --> 00:49:57.100
You asked an important
question.

00:49:57.100 --> 00:49:58.830
Do we love them, or how
do we like them?

00:49:58.830 --> 00:50:02.470
And the answer is I really
do love the instrument.

00:50:02.470 --> 00:50:04.760
And all of us have played on
some older instruments-- and

00:50:04.760 --> 00:50:09.110
I'm also selling an instrument,
not here, today.

00:50:09.110 --> 00:50:12.750
But it's because I think it
should be played by a young

00:50:12.750 --> 00:50:14.390
player that really loves it.

00:50:14.390 --> 00:50:17.590
And I don't need to have more
than one instrument.

00:50:17.590 --> 00:50:20.050
I also have another instrument
that's in that set that we use

00:50:20.050 --> 00:50:23.790
quite often, and its model, as
I said, is on the Stradivari,

00:50:23.790 --> 00:50:24.810
and it's a little brighter.

00:50:24.810 --> 00:50:27.680
And as a second violinist, I
tend more to use it in the

00:50:27.680 --> 00:50:30.710
quartet, and right now, it's
getting a new bridge on it.

00:50:30.710 --> 00:50:32.840
Francis has flown in from
Cremona for a few weeks.

00:50:32.840 --> 00:50:35.130
So I play on this,
which is my own.

00:50:35.130 --> 00:50:36.210
But I love them both.

00:50:36.210 --> 00:50:38.950
And we have to make sure that
our colleagues are happy with

00:50:38.950 --> 00:50:40.960
our instruments, whether
we like it or not.

00:50:40.960 --> 00:50:43.710
The four of us are practically
married in that regard.

00:50:43.710 --> 00:50:46.590
And if things aren't happy at
home, it's just not happy.

00:50:46.590 --> 00:50:49.650
So when I was buying this
violin, Sandy said--

00:50:49.650 --> 00:50:51.860
I wasn't quite sure if I was
going to buy an instrument,

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:54.450
and Sandy said, it'll make
your life a lot easier.

00:50:54.450 --> 00:50:57.380
And sometimes it does.

00:50:57.380 --> 00:50:59.870
But you wanted to hear them
without any amplification.

00:50:59.870 --> 00:51:01.120
I think we can do that.

00:51:08.750 --> 00:51:10.000
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:51:12.990 --> 00:51:15.870
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: This won't
be a listening quiz.

00:51:15.870 --> 00:51:19.140
This will be first part
of the second movement

00:51:19.140 --> 00:51:20.940
of the Mozart quartet.

00:51:20.940 --> 00:51:22.190
[INAUDIBLE] allegretto.

00:51:30.220 --> 00:51:34.970
And this is a lovely space,
and we do appreciate our

00:51:34.970 --> 00:51:36.220
fantastic engineer.

00:51:38.545 --> 00:51:39.539
[INAUDIBLE].

00:51:39.539 --> 00:51:41.030
SANDY WILSON: Just want
to do [INAUDIBLE]?

00:51:41.030 --> 00:51:42.280
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: Yeah.

00:51:44.509 --> 00:53:51.190
[MUSIC - MOZART]

00:53:51.190 --> 00:53:52.120
PAUL YARBROUGH: Better
with, or without?

00:53:52.120 --> 00:53:53.560
AUDIENCE: Without.

00:53:53.560 --> 00:53:55.078
PAUL YARBROUGH: Number
two, OK.

00:53:55.078 --> 00:53:56.910
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: You
have a question.

00:53:56.910 --> 00:53:59.650
AUDIENCE: So I remember when I
was studying chamber music, my

00:53:59.650 --> 00:54:02.550
group would listen to tons of
recordings of other groups

00:54:02.550 --> 00:54:05.250
playing the same pieces, and
evaluate them, and decide

00:54:05.250 --> 00:54:07.780
which one we liked best, and
watch tons of YouTube videos

00:54:07.780 --> 00:54:09.510
of different performances.

00:54:09.510 --> 00:54:11.380
But I was wondering,
what's your, like--

00:54:11.380 --> 00:54:12.550
an established quartet?

00:54:12.550 --> 00:54:15.830
Do you ever go check out the
Saint Lawrence Quartet in

00:54:15.830 --> 00:54:18.310
residency at Stanford to hear
some of their performances?

00:54:18.310 --> 00:54:21.190
Or I know members of the San
Francisco Company sometimes do

00:54:21.190 --> 00:54:23.460
Sunday chamber music
performances for fun.

00:54:23.460 --> 00:54:26.006
Do you ever listen to
any of those, or--

00:54:26.006 --> 00:54:27.180
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: That's
a great question.

00:54:27.180 --> 00:54:28.310
I don't know the Saint
Lawrence--

00:54:28.310 --> 00:54:29.560
I'm just kidding.

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:33.600
It's funny.

00:54:33.600 --> 00:54:36.540
Yes and no.

00:54:36.540 --> 00:54:39.550
Part of it's-- some of us
do, more than others.

00:54:39.550 --> 00:54:40.690
Some of us--

00:54:40.690 --> 00:54:47.350
sometimes Zak, who knows how
to use YouTube and other

00:54:47.350 --> 00:54:50.640
things will send us things
to listen to.

00:54:50.640 --> 00:54:51.780
I used to listen quite a bit.

00:54:51.780 --> 00:54:54.490
When we first started, and the
quartet lived in New York, I

00:54:54.490 --> 00:54:56.640
would go here a number of
quartets, because you'd just

00:54:56.640 --> 00:54:58.460
walk out your door in Lincoln
Center, and hear all your

00:54:58.460 --> 00:54:59.950
colleagues, and see them.

00:54:59.950 --> 00:55:03.610
Now I tend to just bump into
people in airports and chat

00:55:03.610 --> 00:55:07.630
about families and kids
and old teachers.

00:55:07.630 --> 00:55:11.540
But it is important, I
think, to listen to

00:55:11.540 --> 00:55:13.300
other artists play.

00:55:13.300 --> 00:55:16.870
In my particular situation, my
feeling is, I listen to other

00:55:16.870 --> 00:55:20.790
works in other genres outside
of the string quartet.

00:55:20.790 --> 00:55:25.170
I'll do a lot more listening
to songs, opera, by these

00:55:25.170 --> 00:55:28.470
various composers, and we
all like a lot of music.

00:55:28.470 --> 00:55:31.240
And there's only so much
time in the day.

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:35.250
And also, if I want to listen
to something in my car, it's

00:55:35.250 --> 00:55:36.940
usually going to be what my
kids want to listen to.

00:55:36.940 --> 00:55:39.280
I have a 7-year-old and a
14-year-old, so you can use

00:55:39.280 --> 00:55:41.830
your imagination.

00:55:41.830 --> 00:55:43.910
It's not Mozart's
string quartets.

00:55:43.910 --> 00:55:45.100
Even though they like
to come once in a

00:55:45.100 --> 00:55:46.510
while to the concert.

00:55:46.510 --> 00:55:50.400
But I do occasionally hear
things, and the answer is, I

00:55:50.400 --> 00:55:52.770
do learn from my colleagues,
and from young groups that

00:55:52.770 --> 00:55:53.500
come and play for us.

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:55.470
We've had a couple of groups
like the [INAUDIBLE] and

00:55:55.470 --> 00:55:57.030
others that have
worked with us.

00:55:57.030 --> 00:55:58.850
They've become world
class ensembles.

00:55:58.850 --> 00:56:00.520
And they will send us things.

00:56:00.520 --> 00:56:04.680
Zak is working on producing
their first recording.

00:56:04.680 --> 00:56:09.100
And I learn a lot from
hearing other people.

00:56:09.100 --> 00:56:11.850
But I don't particularly
spend a lot of time.

00:56:11.850 --> 00:56:13.580
I think you listen more.

00:56:13.580 --> 00:56:16.020
ZAKARIAS GRAFILO: I listen
a fair amount still.

00:56:16.020 --> 00:56:18.720
When I was a student, I used to
listen to recordings quite

00:56:18.720 --> 00:56:20.780
a bit, and I still have
a lot of recordings

00:56:20.780 --> 00:56:22.630
that I go back to.

00:56:22.630 --> 00:56:26.230
I don't listen as much
as I did in the past.

00:56:26.230 --> 00:56:27.700
I probably would like
to listen to more.

00:56:27.700 --> 00:56:31.250
Going to live concerts, probably
hardly ever nowadays,

00:56:31.250 --> 00:56:33.060
mostly because we're so busy.

00:56:33.060 --> 00:56:35.760
We're so busy teaching, we're
so busy rehearsing, playing

00:56:35.760 --> 00:56:37.790
our own concerts.

00:56:37.790 --> 00:56:40.790
And I don't know if I had the
free time, if I would

00:56:40.790 --> 00:56:43.570
necessarily want to go to
see string quartets.

00:56:43.570 --> 00:56:47.190
I think since we spend so much
time doing it ourselves, like

00:56:47.190 --> 00:56:49.680
what Fred said, kind of getting
away from what we do

00:56:49.680 --> 00:56:52.380
every day is kind of nice.

00:56:52.380 --> 00:56:55.640
But I spend a fair amount of
time on YouTube, and watch

00:56:55.640 --> 00:56:58.020
videos, and listen
to recordings.

00:56:58.020 --> 00:57:00.790
It's fun, when I do have
the time late at night.

00:57:00.790 --> 00:57:03.110
SANDY WILSON: I have
to chime in.

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:07.580
Recently, there was a movie,
some of you may have seen it,

00:57:07.580 --> 00:57:09.285
called A Late Quartet.

00:57:12.300 --> 00:57:16.560
It was mostly in art cinema
houses and such, but Philip

00:57:16.560 --> 00:57:19.680
Seymour Hoffman and Christopher
Walken were in

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:20.600
this movie.

00:57:20.600 --> 00:57:22.780
They were both in the
string quartet.

00:57:22.780 --> 00:57:27.700
And I went, at the sort of
urging of a friend of mine,

00:57:27.700 --> 00:57:29.990
who really wanted to see it and
really wanted me to come

00:57:29.990 --> 00:57:32.150
and see it, too, with her.

00:57:32.150 --> 00:57:33.450
And so I went.

00:57:33.450 --> 00:57:37.950
And I thought I was going to
hate it, because I thought it

00:57:37.950 --> 00:57:40.950
was just going to be baloney.

00:57:40.950 --> 00:57:43.200
It's not really like
this, you know?

00:57:43.200 --> 00:57:45.500
And of course, then you have
to watch these people who

00:57:45.500 --> 00:57:47.700
don't really play instruments
pretend to be playing

00:57:47.700 --> 00:57:51.160
instruments, which is kind
of painful for us.

00:57:51.160 --> 00:57:54.300
But in the end, I really thought
it was terrific.

00:57:54.300 --> 00:57:55.870
I haven't been able
to persuade anyone

00:57:55.870 --> 00:57:57.040
else to go see it.

00:57:57.040 --> 00:57:58.010
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: I went
to see it, and it

00:57:58.010 --> 00:58:00.060
wasn't showing anymore.

00:58:00.060 --> 00:58:00.640
SANDY WILSON: Yeah.

00:58:00.640 --> 00:58:03.470
But it really was quite
well done, I thought.

00:58:03.470 --> 00:58:07.550
And they did a lot of fact
checking, and they must have

00:58:07.550 --> 00:58:12.440
had some great consultation to
get the internal things in

00:58:12.440 --> 00:58:14.370
quartets kind of right.

00:58:14.370 --> 00:58:15.460
It was funny--

00:58:15.460 --> 00:58:19.080
one of the first scenes, there's
some problem after

00:58:19.080 --> 00:58:21.980
which we discover that the
cellist has incipient

00:58:21.980 --> 00:58:24.000
Parkinson's disease.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:28.010
But the first violinist stops,
and he says, our vibratos

00:58:28.010 --> 00:58:30.560
aren't matching.

00:58:30.560 --> 00:58:33.340
And I went, like, did
I hear him say that?

00:58:33.340 --> 00:58:35.150
Because it's exactly
the thing that we

00:58:35.150 --> 00:58:37.830
would say to one another.

00:58:37.830 --> 00:58:39.890
So they really did do
a good job in that.

00:58:39.890 --> 00:58:42.590
I had to tell you about that,
because I thought that movie

00:58:42.590 --> 00:58:47.340
was very insightful for
what you asked.

00:58:47.340 --> 00:58:51.920
Do we still immerse ourselves
in all this stuff?

00:58:51.920 --> 00:58:53.740
And to some extent, we do.

00:58:53.740 --> 00:58:56.741
But also, we need a break.

00:58:56.741 --> 00:58:57.150
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:58:57.150 --> 00:58:59.010
Thank you very much.

00:58:59.010 --> 00:59:02.730
How have your careers evolved
differently than, perhaps, the

00:59:02.730 --> 00:59:05.830
vision that you set yourselves
when you first started?

00:59:05.830 --> 00:59:10.250
And as you're trying to
establish yourselves as young

00:59:10.250 --> 00:59:15.760
artists, what hurdles did you
face that perhaps surprised

00:59:15.760 --> 00:59:18.330
you, and you had to find
creative solutions for?

00:59:18.330 --> 00:59:23.440
SANDY WILSON: Well, if you had
told me when I was 19 years

00:59:23.440 --> 00:59:29.800
old that at the age I am now,
which I won't say, that I

00:59:29.800 --> 00:59:34.350
would be playing in a string
quartet, performing widely,

00:59:34.350 --> 00:59:39.470
teaching at a university,
teaching music, and making a

00:59:39.470 --> 00:59:42.660
living, I would've said
where do I sign?

00:59:42.660 --> 00:59:47.440
I mean, this life that I live
is almost exactly what I

00:59:47.440 --> 00:59:50.660
dreamt of as a young musician
starting out.

00:59:50.660 --> 00:59:54.760
So I'm really very,
very fortunate.

00:59:54.760 --> 00:59:59.450
As far as the challenges that
we face, I think the hardest

00:59:59.450 --> 01:00:02.790
part has always been that
as a quartet you're

01:00:02.790 --> 01:00:04.930
like a small startup--

01:00:04.930 --> 01:00:08.770
a business where you can't
afford to just do your own

01:00:08.770 --> 01:00:11.320
narrow area of expertise.

01:00:11.320 --> 01:00:13.760
You have to wear
a lot of hats.

01:00:13.760 --> 01:00:17.210
And everybody has to be willing
to do things that

01:00:17.210 --> 01:00:19.780
weren't necessarily part
of their curriculum and

01:00:19.780 --> 01:00:21.420
conservatory.

01:00:21.420 --> 01:00:28.900
Like, think about finances and
grant applications, and how to

01:00:28.900 --> 01:00:34.000
organize students into chamber
music ensembles, and keep the

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:37.150
ruffled feathers from
flaring up.

01:00:37.150 --> 01:00:43.210
And I mean, we do a lot of
things for ourselves.

01:00:43.210 --> 01:00:48.340
We book our own travel, we drive
our own rental cars.

01:00:48.340 --> 01:00:54.260
And everything is kind
of small scale.

01:00:54.260 --> 01:01:00.150
And if you like that, if that
kind of endeavor is

01:01:00.150 --> 01:01:02.730
fulfilling, then
this is great.

01:01:02.730 --> 01:01:06.100
If you really hate doing
anything for yourself--

01:01:06.100 --> 01:01:09.640
I mean, the symphony musicians,
they sit their

01:01:09.640 --> 01:01:12.960
suitcases outside their hotel
room, and someone picks it up

01:01:12.960 --> 01:01:17.120
and puts it in the truck, and
they show up when they're

01:01:17.120 --> 01:01:21.070
supposed to be there and play
their instruments, and that's

01:01:21.070 --> 01:01:21.770
pretty much it.

01:01:21.770 --> 01:01:24.710
They don't really need to do
all these other things.

01:01:24.710 --> 01:01:27.930
For us, it's impossible for
us to hire people to do

01:01:27.930 --> 01:01:29.230
everything that we need to do.

01:01:29.230 --> 01:01:33.480
So as a small business, we're
kind of on our own.

01:01:33.480 --> 01:01:35.010
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: I never
thought I would agree 100%

01:01:35.010 --> 01:01:38.000
with Paul, because in a string
quartet, you hardly do.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:41.330
But actually, I think he said
it quite beautifully.

01:01:41.330 --> 01:01:44.080
I grew up watching two things
growing up in Boston-- the

01:01:44.080 --> 01:01:48.360
Boston Celtics, and the great
string quartets that came

01:01:48.360 --> 01:01:51.360
through to Harvard University
and to Jordan

01:01:51.360 --> 01:01:52.220
Hall, and other things.

01:01:52.220 --> 01:01:54.330
And it was my dream to play
second violin in one of the

01:01:54.330 --> 01:01:56.650
great quartets, because I was
enamored with some of the

01:01:56.650 --> 01:01:57.190
second violinists.

01:01:57.190 --> 01:02:01.200
So my other side of that was the
Boston Celtics, but I was

01:02:01.200 --> 01:02:02.760
a little challenged in
some areas there.

01:02:02.760 --> 01:02:05.430
So I play in other
types of parquet

01:02:05.430 --> 01:02:07.300
floors, but with a violin.

01:02:07.300 --> 01:02:12.050
So actually, I think when I
joined the quartet-- that's

01:02:12.050 --> 01:02:12.730
another thing about--

01:02:12.730 --> 01:02:14.810
I talked to my brothers, who
are in business and in

01:02:14.810 --> 01:02:15.560
software and in other things.

01:02:15.560 --> 01:02:16.700
And another thing about
the quartet--

01:02:16.700 --> 01:02:20.200
when I joined this quartet, I
fully anticipated that I would

01:02:20.200 --> 01:02:24.840
lose a little hair, become
gray, and see myself--

01:02:24.840 --> 01:02:27.340
I saw myself as a lifetime
commitment.

01:02:27.340 --> 01:02:30.260
It was 26 years ago when
I joined these guys.

01:02:30.260 --> 01:02:34.490
And I haven't changed that sense
of commitment to it.

01:02:34.490 --> 01:02:37.460
We do from time to time get
upset with each other.

01:02:37.460 --> 01:02:41.690
We function as a group,
like a democracy.

01:02:41.690 --> 01:02:43.580
But we don't have
majority rule.

01:02:43.580 --> 01:02:46.780
All four of us have to agree
100% on every decision we

01:02:46.780 --> 01:02:50.130
make, whether it's where we
play, what fee we accept, what

01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:52.840
airline we fly, or we fly
separate flights.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:56.950
All this stuff, we have to agree
100%, or we don't do it.

01:02:56.950 --> 01:02:58.930
So three to one doesn't win.

01:02:58.930 --> 01:03:02.380
So that also has kept us very
vested in what we do.

01:03:02.380 --> 01:03:05.060
But as far as a career, as far
as the dreams of a young kid--

01:03:05.060 --> 01:03:07.450
I mean, until I look in the
mirror, I still think I'm like

01:03:07.450 --> 01:03:08.800
16 or 17 years old.

01:03:08.800 --> 01:03:11.040
And according to my wife,
I act a little younger.

01:03:11.040 --> 01:03:15.990
So I fully anticipate, as Paul
said, I would be doing this.

01:03:15.990 --> 01:03:18.930
I would be here with you all
today, playing Schubert and

01:03:18.930 --> 01:03:20.210
Mozart, and loving it.

01:03:20.210 --> 01:03:21.640
So I'm pretty lucky.

01:03:25.900 --> 01:03:26.790
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for coming today.

01:03:26.790 --> 01:03:28.640
I was wondering if you could
comment on the sort of

01:03:28.640 --> 01:03:33.020
interplay between technique and
musicality, and whether

01:03:33.020 --> 01:03:35.830
you're making decisions based on
expediency, or based on the

01:03:35.830 --> 01:03:37.710
quality of the music.

01:03:37.710 --> 01:03:39.100
ZAKARIAS GRAFILO: That's a
really great question, and I

01:03:39.100 --> 01:03:41.980
think that's something that we,
as professional musicians,

01:03:41.980 --> 01:03:46.570
struggle with throughout
our careers--

01:03:46.570 --> 01:03:49.920
trying to find ways to be
efficient, but still

01:03:49.920 --> 01:03:51.170
speak to the music.

01:03:53.420 --> 01:03:56.380
I don't know if I have a
real answer for you.

01:03:56.380 --> 01:03:58.310
I think it's something
that, like I said, we

01:03:58.310 --> 01:03:59.890
struggle with every day.

01:03:59.890 --> 01:04:03.100
We rehearse every day for four
or five hours in the morning,

01:04:03.100 --> 01:04:05.630
and these are the kinds of
things that we talk about.

01:04:05.630 --> 01:04:10.670
We're constantly checking
each other.

01:04:10.670 --> 01:04:13.220
Is this a good musical idea?

01:04:13.220 --> 01:04:16.180
Does this make sense
interpretively?

01:04:16.180 --> 01:04:19.000
But we are also talking about
mechanics, too-- the mechanics

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:21.230
of playing together, the
mechanics of playing in tune,

01:04:21.230 --> 01:04:22.790
the mechanics of matching
our vibratos,

01:04:22.790 --> 01:04:24.670
matching the bow speeds.

01:04:24.670 --> 01:04:26.890
So there's always
a balance there

01:04:26.890 --> 01:04:28.580
between those two things.

01:04:28.580 --> 01:04:32.140
The mechanics of playing and
playing together, and being

01:04:32.140 --> 01:04:36.510
musical, and interpreting the
music the best possible way.

01:04:36.510 --> 01:04:39.490
SANDY WILSON: It's something
that's particularly rewarding,

01:04:39.490 --> 01:04:45.170
when you do it in an intimate
team like this with three

01:04:45.170 --> 01:04:45.730
other people.

01:04:45.730 --> 01:04:50.520
Because you draw on the
amplitudes and the strengths

01:04:50.520 --> 01:04:51.335
of one another.

01:04:51.335 --> 01:04:54.870
There are some things that
somebody's going to hate to

01:04:54.870 --> 01:04:58.180
do, but that somebody else just
loves to roll up their

01:04:58.180 --> 01:05:00.070
sleeves and get in with that.

01:05:00.070 --> 01:05:06.860
So we might have the intonation
Nazi, or the

01:05:06.860 --> 01:05:09.860
vibrato Nazi, or the guy who's
going to say, no, we just have

01:05:09.860 --> 01:05:10.540
to routine this.

01:05:10.540 --> 01:05:11.420
We're going to slow this down.

01:05:11.420 --> 01:05:15.070
We're doing this spot, we're
doing that spot.

01:05:15.070 --> 01:05:18.640
But the process, we've
refined it.

01:05:18.640 --> 01:05:20.756
There are certainly some times
when we're really under the

01:05:20.756 --> 01:05:22.685
gun, and we go into the practice
room and say, we

01:05:22.685 --> 01:05:23.900
really have to microwave this.

01:05:23.900 --> 01:05:27.020
We're not going to
make it on time.

01:05:27.020 --> 01:05:28.820
We pull extra rehearsals.

01:05:28.820 --> 01:05:31.520
We do what we have to do,
and our families pay.

01:05:31.520 --> 01:05:33.020
I mean, they really--

01:05:33.020 --> 01:05:34.310
it's a family business.

01:05:34.310 --> 01:05:40.020
We all have spouses and
kids, and it's tough.

01:05:40.020 --> 01:05:45.160
I don't think that many
orchestral musicians--

01:05:45.160 --> 01:05:45.860
professionals--

01:05:45.860 --> 01:05:50.410
really understand what the life
of the string quartet is.

01:05:50.410 --> 01:05:54.730
They will tell us, and we'll nod
in appreciation when they

01:05:54.730 --> 01:05:56.840
tell us, oh, you guys
are so lucky.

01:05:56.840 --> 01:05:58.090
It's just fantastic--

01:05:58.090 --> 01:05:59.680
you're doing everything
we wanted to do.

01:05:59.680 --> 01:06:03.240
But it's like, as Paul says, I
mean, these guys just show up

01:06:03.240 --> 01:06:04.120
at the concert.

01:06:04.120 --> 01:06:07.080
The bus takes them there, and
their tailcoats are already

01:06:07.080 --> 01:06:08.930
pressed, their shoes
are polished.

01:06:08.930 --> 01:06:10.170
They just have to go out,
play the concert,

01:06:10.170 --> 01:06:13.340
and then that's it.

01:06:13.340 --> 01:06:14.740
It's not like that.

01:06:14.740 --> 01:06:16.790
This is really--

01:06:16.790 --> 01:06:18.650
it's a grind.

01:06:18.650 --> 01:06:25.580
But the reward is that we are
all doing exactly what I think

01:06:25.580 --> 01:06:30.210
we aspired to do, even if
we didn't know we did.

01:06:30.210 --> 01:06:33.490
It's so satisfying,
to go to work and

01:06:33.490 --> 01:06:37.110
to have people applaud.

01:06:37.110 --> 01:06:40.280
It's a wonderful privilege.

01:06:40.280 --> 01:06:42.190
And I think we recognize
it as a privilege.

01:06:42.190 --> 01:06:44.640
We really do recognize
we're also--

01:06:44.640 --> 01:06:47.940
we've been very lucky to be
still doing this into our

01:06:47.940 --> 01:06:49.600
fourth decade now.

01:06:49.600 --> 01:06:51.530
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: I think the
great thing about the quartet,

01:06:51.530 --> 01:06:53.910
and I think why a lot of young
people get excited about it,

01:06:53.910 --> 01:06:55.560
is that you are a member
of a team.

01:06:55.560 --> 01:06:56.560
You're part of an ensemble.

01:06:56.560 --> 01:06:59.860
But you're also a soloist,
because of the transparency.

01:06:59.860 --> 01:07:01.580
You're the only one
who's playing

01:07:01.580 --> 01:07:03.270
that part in the group.

01:07:03.270 --> 01:07:06.700
And so you have really the
best of both worlds.

01:07:06.700 --> 01:07:08.480
And it's a fine balancing act.

01:07:08.480 --> 01:07:12.620
I also have to say, much
like Sandy just said--

01:07:12.620 --> 01:07:14.530
I used to play for [INAUDIBLE]
in the Boston Symphony.

01:07:14.530 --> 01:07:16.550
When my colleagues come and hear
us play, or hear us on

01:07:16.550 --> 01:07:18.580
the radio, or hear one of our
recordings, and they say,

01:07:18.580 --> 01:07:20.720
you've gotten so much better.

01:07:20.720 --> 01:07:22.230
I can't imagine how bad
I was at the time.

01:07:22.230 --> 01:07:27.660
But it it's really a testament
to the kind of criticism--

01:07:27.660 --> 01:07:31.700
daily criticism, and support
that we get from one another.

01:07:31.700 --> 01:07:34.040
Because we know that you
have to balance--

01:07:34.040 --> 01:07:36.450
and I think it's true in any
business-- you have to balance

01:07:36.450 --> 01:07:40.450
how hard you push each other and
the effectiveness with the

01:07:40.450 --> 01:07:42.640
overall health of the
organization.

01:07:42.640 --> 01:07:45.340
And we're not an organization
where people quit very often,

01:07:45.340 --> 01:07:47.240
or resign, or leave.

01:07:47.240 --> 01:07:50.710
There've been very few changes
in the quartet.

01:07:50.710 --> 01:07:54.410
I'm the second second violinist
in 31 years, and Zak

01:07:54.410 --> 01:07:59.260
is maybe the fourth
first violinist.

01:07:59.260 --> 01:08:03.663
The first one didn't stay very
long, the second one did for a

01:08:03.663 --> 01:08:06.960
few years, and the third
one 10 years out.

01:08:06.960 --> 01:08:09.370
But we go through first
violinists.

01:08:09.370 --> 01:08:11.480
But we've also known
Zak a long time.

01:08:11.480 --> 01:08:13.410
We've known him since he was
a kid in San Francisco.

01:08:13.410 --> 01:08:18.819
So it's a real balancing
act in the work

01:08:18.819 --> 01:08:19.779
that we have to do.

01:08:19.779 --> 01:08:21.410
Thank you for having us today.

01:08:21.410 --> 01:08:23.630
The San Francisco
Performance--

01:08:23.630 --> 01:08:26.210
Virginia-- for bringing
us down here.

01:08:26.210 --> 01:08:28.609
We don't live that far away, so
if you ever want to have us

01:08:28.609 --> 01:08:31.550
back, I think you know
how to find us.

01:08:31.550 --> 01:08:34.540
And you can Google us
and find out more.

01:08:34.540 --> 01:08:37.500
I always wanted to
say that there.

01:08:37.500 --> 01:08:40.549
Because it's just part
of our life.

01:08:40.549 --> 01:08:42.630
And, I mean, my kids think
they're so smart, because they

01:08:42.630 --> 01:08:43.779
can Google everything.

01:08:43.779 --> 01:08:46.979
And that's not a substitute
for intelligence, but it's

01:08:46.979 --> 01:08:48.340
very useful.

01:08:48.340 --> 01:08:50.600
But it's really been
a pleasure.

01:08:50.600 --> 01:08:52.359
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:08:52.359 --> 01:08:53.810
doesn't know what he's
talking about.

01:08:53.810 --> 01:08:56.260
FREDERICK LIFSITZ: Yeah.

01:08:56.260 --> 01:09:00.700
And thank you, Cliff, so
much for all this.

01:09:00.700 --> 01:09:03.029
So we'll be packing
our things up.

01:09:03.029 --> 01:09:05.140
If you want to take a look at
the instruments, or chat a

01:09:05.140 --> 01:09:08.069
little bit, some of us won't be
running right out the door.

01:09:08.069 --> 01:09:09.970
So thank you.

